solution.p:
What we need to do is to translate this physical situation into mathematics, and to do that we need to start assigning names to the quantities of interest. The quantities that matter in this problem are the movement of the ball, the force of gravity and the force of air resistance. We'll name them as follows:
\text{height of the ball t seconds after its released} &= y(t) \text{force of gravity} &= F_{G} = mg = -4.9 \text{force of air resistance} &= F_{R} = k\dv{y}{t}
where C is negative (since air resistance should act against velocity). To get a differential equation out of all this, we'll use Newton's Second Law (which is actually a second-order ODE in disguise). This says that the net force on the ball should be equal to its mass times acceleration: F = ma. So we have F_{G}+F_{R} = 0.5\dv[2]{y}{t} or just -4.9+k\dv{y}{t} = 0.5\dv[2]{y}{t}. The initial condition in this case would be y(0) = 100. So our IVP is -4.9+k\dv{y}{t} = 0.5\dv[2]{y}{t}, y(0) = 100.

image.asymptote:
import graph;
import slopefield;

//This gives the size of the figure.
size(200);

//This is to draw the slope field.
real func1(real x, real y) {return y*(1-y);}
add(slopefield(func1,(-3,-3),(3,3),20,deepgreen));

//This draws the axes.
xaxis("$t$",xmin=-3,xmax=3.3,fontsize(11pt),LeftTicks,ArcArrow(SimpleHead));
yaxis("$x$",ymin=-3,ymax=3.3,fontsize(11pt),RightTicks,ArcArrow(SimpleHead));

import graph;
import slopefield;
import fontsize;
defaultpen(fontsize(9pt));
size(200);

//This is to draw the slope field.
real func1(real x, real y) {return y*(1-y);}
real xmin=-3, xmax=3;
real ymin=-3, ymax=3;

add(slopefield(func1,(xmin,ymin),(xmax,ymax),20,deepgreen+0.4bp,Arrow));

pair C=(0,0.5);
draw(curve(C,func1,(xmin,ymin),(xmax,ymax)),deepblue+1bp);

label("$(0,\frac{1}{2})$",C,NE,UnFill);
dot(C,UnFill);

//This draws the axes.
xaxis("$t$",xmin=-3,xmax=3.3,fontsize(11pt),LeftTicks,ArcArrow(SimpleHead));
yaxis("$x$",ymin=-3,ymax=3.3,fontsize(11pt),RightTicks,ArcArrow(SimpleHead));
